By a strange co-incidence, I read your posting on the very day that
the latest edition of the Oxford University Computing Services'
Newsletter came out.  One of the articles in it is by me and covers
PGP and its use for protecting and signing email and files.  To
demonstrate what a PGP-signed message looks like, the entire printed
article is PGP-signed.  That is, the -----BEGIN PGP SIGNED
MESSAGE-----, -----BEGIN PGP SIGNATURE-----, etc actually appears in
the printed text.

Needless to say, the signature is useless to the reader, but it *is*
the PGP signature of the article as I submitted it to the editor.

Paul
